<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-09-29T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-09-29T18:00:00-05:00" n="528" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d528">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94116/107: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bucknell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-09-30T00:00:00+01:00">September 30,
                                    1938—midnight.</date><lb/>[Received September 30—7:10
                                p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>260. My No. 254, September 29, 8 p.m. The Council today adopted the
                            resolution providing for investigation of Chinese charges of use of
                            poison gas by Japanese without change in text already reported. British
                            stated that this was best method of inquiry at least in first instance
                            and China in accepting resolution reserved the right to ask Council to
                            take further action if present procedure proved to be ineffective.
                            Council session closed tonight.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bucknell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
